meta.description:
Mauritius is a multicultural society. Throughout its short history, people have voluntarily or involuntarily come to the island from various parts of the Indian Ocean and the African, Asian and European continents. They have brought with them forms of traditional cultural expressions from their countries of origins. This meeting of cultures has also produced new forms of traditional cultural expressions that are today unique to the Republic of Mauritius. The present project proposal aims at identifying and documenting this heritage in a first phase. This shall later allow for the design of activities to help promote awareness and sensitize people to this heritage. The project intends:
•	to identify and document forms of intangible cultural heritage within the Republic of Mauritius;
•	to produce an inventory and a database of this heritage;
•	to provide a repository for this heritage;
•	to be able to identify the state of conservation of this heritage;
•	to manage and monitor impact of development projects in relation to this heritage;
•	to design products for the dissemination of knowledge related to this heritage.
The inventory project will be carried out by the National Heritage Fund that operates under the aegis of the Ministry of Education, Culture and Human Resources.

At the time of inscription of the Aapravasi Ghat on the World Heritage List the World Heritage Committee recommended that the Aapravasi Ghat Trust Fund (AGTF) “undertake research on indentured labour to consider the extent, scope and impact of the indentured labour Diaspora around the world” (WHC-06/30.COM/19; Decision 30 COM 8B.33). Through this project, the AGTF aims at setting up an inventory of elements of intangible heritage related to the history of indenture in line with its mission and objectives contained in the Management Plan of the Aapravasi Ghat World Heritage Property. The project has as its objectives:
•	to identify and safeguard the Mauritian intangible heritage pertaining to the history of indenture;
•	to preserve and promote the languages spoken by the indentured labourers and also old forms of Mauritian Creole referring to the indenture experience;
•	to document in-depth the indenture history from an intangible perspective;
•	to solicit the participation of the community and encourage community involvement;
•	to identify elements of intangible heritage for possible inscription on the Lists of the 2003 Convention
The Aapravasi Ghat Trust Fund shall be responsible for the implementation of the project. The AGTF is a corporate body operating under the aegis of the Ministry of Education, Culture and Human Resources with responsibilities to manage, protect and promote the Aapravasi Ghat and all aspects pertaining to indenture.
